<div class="dablink">For gestures in computing, see <a href="/wiki/Mouse_gesture" title="Mouse gesture">mouse gesture</a>.</div>
<div class="dablink">"Gestures" redirects here. For the rock group, see <a href="/wiki/The_Gestures" title="The Gestures">The Gestures</a>.</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Us_navy_helicopter_landing_signals_illustration.jpg" class="image" title="Military signalmen use hand and body gestures to direct flight operations aboard aircraft carriers."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/Us_navy_helicopter_landing_signals_illustration.jpg/200px-Us_navy_helicopter_landing_signals_illustration.jpg" width="200" height="194" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Us_navy_helicopter_landing_signals_illustration.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Military signalmen use hand and body gestures to direct flight operations aboard aircraft carriers.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>A <b>gesture</b> is a form of <a href="/wiki/Non-verbal_communication" title="Non-verbal communication" class="mw-redirect">non-verbal communication</a> made with a part of the body, used instead of or in combination with <i>verbal communication</i>. The language of gesture allows individuals to express a variety of feelings and thoughts, from contempt and hostility to approval and affection. Most people use gestures and <a href="/wiki/Body_language" title="Body language">body language</a> in addition to <a href="/wiki/Word" title="Word">words</a> when they speak. The use of gesture as language by some ethnic groups is more common than in others, and the amount of such gesturing that is considered culturally acceptable varies from one location to the next.</p>
